The ternary Padovan morphism $S arrow.r M, M arrow.r L, L arrow.r S M$ resolves a tension that the binary case leaves open. Among ternary substitutions admissible under the same constraints (stability, ratio bounded by the shuffle threshold $L slash S < 2$, perceptual viability in the groove window), the Padovan rule is the _unique_ admissible candidate. The plurality observed in the binary case — multiple rules optimising different properties — collapses into a single rule in the ternary case. This consolidation is not a simplification of the framework but a structural fact about what three-duration substitution rules can do, anchored in a sharp result of algebraic number theory: the absence of admissible Pisot inflations between $rho$ and the next algebraic candidate.#footnote[The technical formulation of this uniqueness, together with the Pisot gap that grounds it, is given in @sec:synthesis of Book IV. The same section provides the formal catalogue of admissible binary rules and the comparison with the ternary case.] The move from binary to ternary is therefore not a quantitative extension but a qualitative consolidation: properties distributed across several binary rules coalesce into one ternary rule.

This is the structure of the triad. $sqrt(2)$ answers the question of the paired subdivision, and answers it twice — once with compactness, once with stability. $phi.alt$ answers the question of stable binary recursion, with the unique combination of stability, minimal inflation, and maximal interleaving among binary rules. $rho$ answers the question of ternary consolidation, with the unique admissible three-duration rule. The three proportions are not three numbers that appear in three unrelated contexts; they are the three positions that are structurally forced once the substitution framework is taken seriously, and once the constraints of musical perception are applied.

Two consequences deserve brief mention before the framework is closed. First, the swing positions associated with the triad cover the practical range of rhythmic swing with structurally determined waypoints: $sqrt(2)$ at the meantone of @sec:tempering (50% binary swing), $phi.alt$ at the medium-swing position of mainstream jazz, $rho^2$ at the heavier swing characteristic of the samba zone. The three proportions act as anchors in the continuum of swing feel, with the rest of the range available as morphing between them. Second, the framework as developed here stops at the ternary case. Whether the binary plurality reappears in the quaternary case, or whether the ternary uniqueness generalises to all higher arities, is an open question; Book IV briefly examines the conditions a quaternary candidate would have to satisfy and notes that the answer depends on facts about higher-degree algebraic integers that lie outside the scope of the present work.

With the triad in place, the framework developed in this chapter is complete in its essentials. What remains is to state formally what a _fractal rhythm_ is — to extract from the preceding constructions the abstract object they have been pointing toward — and to examine the properties that follow from this definition.
